<paragraph blockId="43.[684,1212,1505,1739]" pageId="43" pageNumber="43">
IDENTIFICATION: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kaup" authorityYear="1829" box="[924,996,1610,1633]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="43" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[924,996,1610,1633]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="43">Myotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the most diverse and widely distributed bat genus with 126 species recognized (
<bibRefCitation author="Burgin, C. J. &amp; J. P. Colella &amp; P. L. Kahn &amp; N. S. Upham" box="[820,1032,1679,1703]" pageId="43" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref33565" refString="Burgin, C. J., J. P. Colella, P. L. Kahn, and N. S. Upham. 2018. How many species of mammals are there? Journal of Mammalogy 99: 1 - 14." type="journal article" year="2018">Burgin et al., 2018</bibRefCitation>
). The taxonomy and systematics of the genus, especially in the
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[108,638,225,1176]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">
New World, is confused and controversial (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="LaVal, R. K." box="[108,246,259,284]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 54" refId="ref38194" refString="LaVal, R. K. 1973. A revision of the Neotropical bats of the genus Myotis. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County 15: 1 - 54." type="journal article" year="1973">LaVal, 1973</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Moratelli, R. &amp; J. A. de Oliveira" box="[263,631,259,284]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="789 - 802" refId="ref39702" refString="Moratelli, R., and J. A. de Oliveira. 2011. Morphometric and morphological variation in South American populations of Myotis albescens (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae). Zoologia 28: 789 - 802." type="journal article" year="2011">Moratelli and de Oliveira, 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Peracchi &amp; J. A. de Oliveira" box="[108,343,294,318]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="41 - 54" refId="ref39827" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Peracchi, and J. A. de Oliveira. 2011 a. Morphometric and morphological variation in Myotis simus Thomas (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae), with an appraisal of the identity of Myotis guaycuru Proenca based on the analysis of the type material. Zootaxa 2985: 41 - 54." type="journal article" year="2011">
Moratelli et al., 2011 
<bibRefCitation author="Larsen, P. A. &amp; M. R. Marchan-Rivadeneira &amp; R. J. Baker" box="[331,343,294,318]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="315 - 339" refId="ref38081" refString="Larsen, P. A., M. R. Marchan-Rivadeneira, and R. J. Baker. 2013. Speciation dynamics of the fruit-eating bats (genus Artibeus): with evidence of ecological divergence in Central American populations. In R. A. Adams and S. C. Pedersen (editors), Bat evolution, ecology, and conservation: 315 - 339. New York: Springer." type="book chapter" year="2013">a</bibRefCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
,b, 2013; 
<bibRefCitation author="Moratelli, R. &amp; D. E. Wilson" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="115 - 121" refId="ref39741" refString="Moratelli, R., and D. E. Wilson. 2011. The identity of Myotis punensis (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae). Zoologia 28: 115 - 121." type="journal article" year="2011">Moratelli and Wilson, 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Marchan-Rivadeneira, M. R. &amp; P. A. Larsen &amp; C. J. Phillips &amp; R. E. Strauss &amp; R. J. Baker" box="[221,412,328,352]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="623 - 634" refId="ref39181" refString="Marchan-Rivadeneira, M. R., P. A. Larsen, C. J. Phillips, R. E. Strauss, and R. J. Baker. 2012. On the association between environmental gradients and skull size variation in the great fruit-eating bat, Artibeus lituratus (Chiroptera: Phyllostomidae). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 105: 623 - 634." type="journal article" year="2012">Larsen et al., 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mantilla-Meluk, H. &amp; J. Munoz-Garay" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="60 - 70" refId="ref39094" refString="Mantilla-Meluk, H., and J. Munoz-Garay. 2014. Biogeography and taxonomic status of Myotis keaysi pilosatibialis LaVal 1973 (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae). Zootaxa 3793: 60 - 70." type="journal article" year="2014">Mantilla-Meluk and Muñoz-Garay, 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Recently, several studies have attempted to clarify the taxonomy of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schinz" baseAuthorityYear="1821" box="[108,288,432,455]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nigricans">
<emphasis box="[108,288,432,455]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Myotis nigricans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex (
<bibRefCitation author="Marchan-Rivadeneira, M. R. &amp; P. A. Larsen &amp; C. J. Phillips &amp; R. E. Strauss &amp; R. J. Baker" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="623 - 634" refId="ref39181" refString="Marchan-Rivadeneira, M. R., P. A. Larsen, C. J. Phillips, R. E. Strauss, and R. J. Baker. 2012. On the association between environmental gradients and skull size variation in the great fruit-eating bat, Artibeus lituratus (Chiroptera: Phyllostomidae). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 105: 623 - 634." type="journal article" year="2012">Larsen et al., 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Gardner &amp; J. A. de Oliveira &amp; D. E. Wilson" box="[171,391,465,490]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref39946" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Gardner, J. A. de Oliveira, and D. E. Wilson. 2013. Review of Myotis (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae) from northern South America, including description of a new species. American Museum Novitates 3780: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2013">Moratelli et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Moratelli, R. &amp; D. E. Wilson" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="533 - 542" refId="ref39773" refString="Moratelli, R., and D. E. Wilson. 2014. A second record of Myotis diminutus (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae): its bearing on the taxonomy of the species and discrimination from M. nigricans. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 127: 533 - 542." type="journal article" year="2014">Moratelli and Wilson, 2014</bibRefCitation>
). One of the results of these revisions was the recognition of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="1914" box="[306,482,535,558]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caucensis">
<emphasis box="[306,482,535,558]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Myotis caucensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a valid species where previously it had been regarded as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cornalia" baseAuthorityYear="1849" box="[342,636,603,627]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="nigricans" subSpecies="osculatii">
<emphasis box="[342,636,603,627]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Myotis nigricans osculatii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wilson, D. E." box="[115,273,637,661]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="468 - 481" refId="ref44630" refString="Wilson, D. E. 2008 b (&quot; 2007 &quot;). Genus Myotis Kaup, 1829. In A. L. Gardner (editor), Mammals of South America, vol. 1: Marsupials, xenarthrans, shrews, and bats: 468 - 481. Chicago: University of Chicago Press." type="book chapter" year="2008">Wilson, 2008b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Gardner &amp; J. A. de Oliveira &amp; D. E. Wilson" box="[282,503,637,661]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref39946" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Gardner, J. A. de Oliveira, and D. E. Wilson. 2013. Review of Myotis (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae) from northern South America, including description of a new species. American Museum Novitates 3780: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2013">Moratelli et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="1914" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caucensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">M. caucensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs along the intermontane valleys of the Andes in 
<collectingCountry box="[218,327,706,730]" name="Colombia" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[428,521,706,730]" name="Ecuador" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[585,636,706,729]" name="Peru" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">Peru</collectingCountry>
and the adjacent Amazon lowlands across an elevational range from ca. 
<quantity box="[395,550,774,798]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="0.2" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" unit="m" value="1400.0" valueMax="2600.0" valueMin="200.0">200 to 2600 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="LaVal, R. K." pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 54" refId="ref38194" refString="LaVal, R. K. 1973. A revision of the Neotropical bats of the genus Myotis. Bulletin of the Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County 15: 1 - 54." type="journal article" year="1973">LaVal, 1973</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Gardner &amp; J. A. de Oliveira &amp; D. E. Wilson" box="[177,415,808,833]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref39946" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Gardner, J. A. de Oliveira, and D. E. Wilson. 2013. Review of Myotis (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae) from northern South America, including description of a new species. American Museum Novitates 3780: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2013">Moratelli et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
). No subspecies are currently recognized in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Moratelli et al., 2013)" baseAuthorityName="Moratelli" baseAuthorityYear="2013" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Myotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caucensis">
<emphasis box="[363,497,844,867]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="44">M. caucensis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Gardner &amp; J. A. de Oliveira &amp; D. E. Wilson" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref39946" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Gardner, J. A. de Oliveira, and D. E. Wilson. 2013. Review of Myotis (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae) from northern South America, including description of a new species. American Museum Novitates 3780: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2013">Moratelli et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Our Mayo River basin voucher specimens exhibit the diagnostic characteristics of the species: medium-size (FA 36.0–38.5 mm); dorsal pelage silky and unicolored; a fringe of hairs lacking along the trailing edge of the uropatagium; sagittal crest absent; and frontals not steeply sloping (
<bibRefCitation author="Moratelli, R. &amp; A. L. Gardner &amp; J. A. de Oliveira &amp; D. E. Wilson" box="[157,386,1083,1107]" pageId="44" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 36" refId="ref39946" refString="Moratelli, R., A. L. Gardner, J. A. de Oliveira, and D. E. Wilson. 2013. Review of Myotis (Chiroptera, Vespertilionidae) from northern South America, including description of a new species. American Museum Novitates 3780: 1 - 36." type="journal article" year="2013">Moratelli et al., 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Measurements of our specimens fall within the range of measurements reported for the species.
</paragraph>
